aina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Raby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Raby (Cheshire), recorded as <i>Raby</i> from 1096–1101, Raby in Holme East Waver (Cumberland), recorded as <i>Rabi</i><i>c.</i> 1150, or Raby in Staindrop (Durham), recorded as <i>Raby</i><i>c.</i> 1050. The placenames probably derive from Old Norse <i>rá</i> ‘boundary, pole’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village, settlement’, though the Durham placename may derive from Old Norse <i>rá</i> ‘roe, roe buck’ + <i>bȳ</i>, as it does not lie on a known boundary.","English: in some cases, a variant of   Robey  . Additionally, in southwestern England and the Channel Islands there appears to be a further source for the name, maybe a diminutive of   Robert  .","Altered form of French <b>Desrabines</b> (via the intermediate form <i>Daraby</i>): habitational name, with fused preposition and definite article <i>des</i> ‘from the’, denoting someone from Les Rabines, the name of a few places in Brittany. The surname <i>Desrabines</i> is not found in France. Compare   Roby   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Roby","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Roby in Huyton (Lancashire), from Old Norse <i>rá</i> ‘landmark, boundary’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’. Compare   Raby  .","Scottish: variant of   Robbie  .","Variant of   Raby   3, a surname of French origin."]},{"name":"Rabey","meanings":["English: variant of   Raby  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of Hungarian   Raby   and German   Rabe  ."]},{"name":"Robey","meanings":["English: variant of   Roby  ."]}]},{"name":"Nevil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"